<p>
    In this pod, we will create a formal, mathematical definition
    of mechanical forms of potential energy.
</p>


<p class = 'definition'>
    A system gains <strong>mechanical potential energy</strong>
    whenever a <strong>internal, conservative force</strong>
    does <strong>negative work</strong> on some particle with mass within the system.
    The amount of energy gained is equal to the opposite of the negative work done.
</p>


<h4>
    Example: Gravitational Potential Energy:
</h4>

<p>
    Imagine a book on the floor that is lifted up and placed on a table of height \( h = \Delta y \).
    During this time, the force of <strong>gravity</strong>
    on the book has the direction down and the magnitude \( mg \).
    Because the book is moving upward, and the direction of gravity, is down,
    the work done by gravity is <emph>negative</emph>.
    (Even though the applied force also does positive work on the book,
    gravity still counts as doing negative work.)
    The amount of force done by gravity is \( W = Fd = - ( mg ) \Delta y = -mg \Delta y \).
    Gravity is also a <strong>conservative force</strong>,
    because no matter what path the book takes from the floor to the table,
    the work done by gravity is the same value.
    According to the defintion above, the book-earth system
    gains potential energy equal to \( -W \),
    so \( \Delta PE = - W = - (-mg \Delta y) = mg \Delta y \),
    or \( \Delta GPE = mg \Delta y \).
    If you define the ground to be the zero-point height, at which \( h = 0 \) and \( GPE = 0 \), you have the formula
    we recognize for gravitational potential energy:
    \( GPE = mgh \).
</p>

